  <h1 id="top">Sampling Distributions, CLT &amp; Confidence Intervals</h1>
  <p>The CLT turns any distribution's sample mean into a normal. The CI simulation makes the "95% confidence" meaning concrete — it describes the procedure, not any one interval.</p>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 1: SAMPLE MEAN & SE ═══ -->
<h2 id="sample-mean">Theory — Sampling Distribution of the Mean</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  The sample mean $\bar&#123;X&#125;$ is a random variable. Its distribution — the <strong>sampling distribution</strong> — has mean $\mu$ and spread that shrinks with sample size.
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Mean and variance of $\bar&#123;X&#125;$</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$E[\bar&#123;X&#125;] = \mu, \qquad \text&#123;Var&#125;(\bar&#123;X&#125;) = \frac&#123;\sigma^2&#125;&#123;n&#125;$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Valid for any i.i.d. sample with finite $\mu$ and $\sigma^2$. No normality assumption required.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Standard Error (SE) — SD of the mean</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\text&#123;SE&#125; = \frac&#123;\sigma&#125;&#123;\sqrt&#123;n&#125;&#125; \qquad \text&#123;(shrinks as } 1/\sqrt&#123;n&#125;\text&#123;)}$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Halving SE requires $4\times$ the data. Doubling $n$ reduces SE by $\sqrt&#123;2&#125;$, not 2.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Sum $S_n = \sum X_i$ — scale up</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$E[S_n] = n\mu, \qquad \text&#123;Var&#125;(S_n) = n\sigma^2$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">The sum and mean are linked: $\bar&#123;X&#125; = S_n/n$. Variance scales linearly with $n$ for the sum.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Key trap — SE vs Var</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\text&#123;Var&#125;(\bar&#123;X&#125;) = \frac&#123;\sigma^2&#125;&#123;n&#125; \ne \sigma^2, \qquad \text&#123;SE&#125; = \frac&#123;\sigma&#125;&#123;\sqrt&#123;n&#125;&#125; \ne \sigma$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Standardize $\bar&#123;X&#125;$ with SE, not $\sigma$: $z = (\bar&#123;X&#125; - \mu)/(\sigma/\sqrt&#123;n&#125;)$.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 2: CLT ═══ -->
<h2 id="clt">Theory — Central Limit Theorem</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  For large $n$, the sample mean is approximately normal — <strong>regardless of the parent distribution</strong>. This is the most powerful and quotable result in Module 1.
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">CLT — standardized form</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\frac&#123;\bar&#123;X&#125; - \mu&#125;&#123;\sigma/\sqrt&#123;n&#125;&#125; \xrightarrow&#123;d&#125; N(0,1) \quad\Leftrightarrow\quad \bar&#123;X&#125; \approx N\!\left(\mu,\, \frac&#123;\sigma^2&#125;&#123;n&#125;\right)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Works for any parent with finite variance. For the sum: $S_n \approx N(n\mu,\, n\sigma^2)$.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Normal approximations from CLT</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\text&#123;Bin&#125;(n,p) \approx N(np,\, np(1-p)) \quad \text&#123;Poi&#125;(\lambda) \approx N(\lambda, \lambda)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">For Binomial: large $n$, not too extreme $p$. For Poisson: $\lambda$ large. Standardize with mean and SD from the table. (2025 Q40)</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--insight">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">CLT workflow — three steps every time</span>
    (1) Find $\mu$ and $\sigma^2$ for the parent (or $np$, $np(1-p)$ for Binomial).
    (2) For $\bar&#123;X&#125;$: SE $= \sigma/\sqrt&#123;n&#125;$; for $S_n$: SD $= \sigma\sqrt&#123;n&#125;$.
    (3) Standardize: $z = (\text&#123;value&#125; - \text&#123;mean&#125;)/\text&#123;SD&#125;$, then look up $\Phi$.
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 3: CHI-SQUARED & T ═══ -->
<h2 id="chisq-t">Theory — Chi-Squared &amp; t Distributions</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  These two distributions arise naturally from normal samples. Chi-squared powers variance inference; the t-distribution handles inference when $\sigma$ is unknown.
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Chi-squared $\chi^2(k)$ — definition</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\chi^2(k) = Z_1^2 + Z_2^2 + \cdots + Z_k^2, \qquad E=k,\quad \text&#123;Var&#125;=2k$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Sum of $k$ independent squared standard normals. Support $[0,\infty)$, right-skewed. (2025 Q36: $k=1 \Rightarrow \text&#123;Var&#125;=2$.)</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Sample variance link — $n-1$ degrees of freedom</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\frac&#123;(n-1)S^2&#125;&#123;\sigma^2&#125; = \frac&#123;\sum(X_i-\bar&#123;X&#125;)^2&#125;&#123;\sigma^2&#125; \sim \chi^2(n-1)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Trap: $n-1$ not $n$ — one df lost estimating $\bar&#123;X&#125;$. (2026 Q53 B)</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Student's $t_k$ — heavier tails than normal</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$t_k = \frac&#123;Z&#125;&#123;\sqrt&#123;\chi^2_k/k&#125;&#125;, \quad t_k \to N(0,1) \text&#123; as &#125; k \to \infty$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Symmetric about 0. $t_1 = $ Cauchy (no mean/variance — extreme heavy tails). (2026 Q28)</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">$\chi^2(2) = \text&#123;Exponential&#125;(\text&#123;mean &#125;2)$ identity</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$Z_1^2 + Z_2^2 \sim \chi^2(2) = \text&#123;Exp&#125;\!\left(\text&#123;mean }=2\right)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Sum of 2 squared standard normals = Exponential with mean 2. Handy identity that appears in 2026 Q53 C.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Reference table -->
<div class="rule-card" style="margin-top:16px;">
  <div class="rule-card__label">Quick Reference — Mean &amp; Variance</div>
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1.4fr 1.6fr 0.8fr 0.8fr;gap:4px 8px;margin-top:10px;font-size:13px;">
    <div style="font-family:var(--gd-font-mono);font-size:11px;color:var(--gd-text-2);padding-bottom:4px;border-bottom:1px solid var(--gd-line-soft);">Object</div>
    <div style="font-family:var(--gd-font-mono);font-size:11px;color:var(--gd-text-2);padding-bottom:4px;border-bottom:1px solid var(--gd-line-soft);">Definition</div>
    <div style="font-family:var(--gd-font-mono);font-size:11px;color:var(--gd-text-2);padding-bottom:4px;border-bottom:1px solid var(--gd-line-soft);text-align:center;">Mean</div>
    <div style="font-family:var(--gd-font-mono);font-size:11px;color:var(--gd-text-2);padding-bottom:4px;border-bottom:1px solid var(--gd-line-soft);text-align:center;">Variance</div>
    <div style="color:var(--gd-brand);font-family:var(--gd-font-mono);font-size:12px;">$\bar&#123;X&#125;$</div>
    <div style="color:var(--gd-text-1);">$(1/n)\sum X_i$</div>
    <div style="text-align:center;color:var(--gd-text-1);">$\mu$</div>
    <div style="text-align:center;color:var(--gd-text-1);">$\sigma^2/n$</div>
    <div style="color:var(--gd-brand);font-family:var(--gd-font-mono);font-size:12px;">$S_n$</div>
    <div style="color:var(--gd-text-1);">$\sum X_i$</div>
    <div style="text-align:center;color:var(--gd-text-1);">$n\mu$</div>
    <div style="text-align:center;color:var(--gd-text-1);">$n\sigma^2$</div>
    <div style="color:var(--gd-brand);font-family:var(--gd-font-mono);font-size:12px;">$\chi^2(k)$</div>
    <div style="color:var(--gd-text-1);">$\sum_&#123;i=1&#125;^k Z_i^2$</div>
    <div style="text-align:center;color:var(--gd-text-1);">$k$</div>
    <div style="text-align:center;color:var(--gd-text-1);">$2k$</div>
    <div style="color:var(--gd-brand);font-family:var(--gd-font-mono);font-size:12px;">$t_k$</div>
    <div style="color:var(--gd-text-1);">$Z/\sqrt&#123;\chi^2_k/k&#125;$</div>
    <div style="text-align:center;color:var(--gd-text-1);">$0\ (k>1)$</div>
    <div style="text-align:center;color:var(--gd-text-1);">$k/(k-2)$</div>
  </div>
  <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$t_k$ mean requires $k>1$; variance requires $k>2$. $t_1$ = Cauchy has neither.</p>
</div>

<!-- ═══ VIZ 1: CI COVERAGE SIMULATION ═══ -->
<h2 id="viz1">Interactive 1 — CI Coverage Simulation</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  True $\mu=5$ (orange line). Each button draw yields one CI from a fresh sample of size $n$. Green bars contain $\mu$; red bars miss it. Watch the coverage converge to the stated confidence level.
</p>

<div class="gd-formula-panel gd-formula-panel--split">
  <div>
    <div class="gd-formula-label">Confidence interval formula</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\bar&#123;x&#125; \pm z_&#123;\alpha/2&#125;\,\dfrac&#123;\sigma&#125;&#123;\sqrt&#123;n&#125;&#125;$$</div>
  </div>
  <div>
    <div class="gd-formula-label">Live width</div>
    <div class="gd-formula-live" id="ci-live">—</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="ci-btn-row">
  <button class="ci-btn ci-btn--primary" id="btn-sample1">Draw 1 sample</button>
  <button class="ci-btn" id="btn-sample20">Draw 20 more</button>
  <button class="ci-btn" id="btn-sample100">Draw 100 more</button>
  <button class="ci-btn ci-btn--danger" id="btn-reset">Reset</button>
</div>

<div class="gd-chart" style="position:relative;">
  <div class="gd-chart__title">Green bars contain μ · Red bars miss μ · Orange line = true μ = 5</div>
  <div id="ci-chart"></div>
</div>

<div class="ci-stats">
  <div class="ci-stat"><div class="ci-stat__label">Samples</div><div class="ci-stat__val" id="ci-total">0</div></div>
  <div class="ci-stat"><div class="ci-stat__label">Cover μ</div><div class="ci-stat__val" id="ci-cover" style="color:var(--gd-success)">0</div></div>
  <div class="ci-stat"><div class="ci-stat__label">Miss μ</div><div class="ci-stat__val" id="ci-miss" style="color:var(--gd-error)">0</div></div>
  <div class="ci-stat"><div class="ci-stat__label">Coverage %</div><div class="ci-stat__val" id="ci-pct">—</div></div>
</div>

<div class="gd-controls">
  <div class="gd-controls__title">Parameters</div>
  <div class="gd-control">
    <label class="gd-control__label"><span class="gd-control__sym">n</span> Sample size</label>
    <span class="gd-control__value" id="n-val">30</span>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-control--full"><input class="gd-control__slider" type="range" id="n-slider" min="5" max="100" step="5" value="30"></div>
  <div class="gd-control">
    <label class="gd-control__label"><span class="gd-control__sym">α</span> Significance level → z<sub>α/2</sub></label>
    <span class="gd-control__value" id="alpha-val">0.05 (z=1.96)</span>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-control--full"><input class="gd-control__slider" type="range" id="alpha-slider" min="1" max="4" step="1" value="2"></div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insights__title">Live insights</div>
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--active" id="ci-ins1">Draw samples to see CI coverage.</div>
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--warn" id="ci-ins2">
    ⚠ Key misconception: a single CI does NOT have 95% probability of containing μ — it either does or doesn't. The 95% describes the method, not any one interval.
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ VIZ 2: WIDTH vs N ═══ -->
<h2 id="viz2">Interactive 2 — CI Width vs Sample Size</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  Width $\propto 1/\sqrt&#123;n&#125;$ — halving the width requires $4\times$ the data. The blue dot follows the slider above.
</p>

<div class="gd-formula-panel gd-formula-panel--split">
  <div>
    <div class="gd-formula-label">Width formula</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\text&#123;Width&#125; = 2\,z_&#123;\alpha/2&#125;\,\dfrac&#123;\sigma&#125;&#123;\sqrt&#123;n&#125;&#125;$$</div>
  </div>
  <div>
    <div class="gd-formula-label">Current values</div>
    <div class="gd-formula-live" id="width-live">—</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-chart">
  <div class="gd-chart__title">Width vs n curve · blue dot = current n from slider above</div>
  <div id="width-chart"></div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ WORKED EXAMPLES ═══ -->
<h2 id="examples">Worked Examples</h2>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 1 · CLT for a sample mean</span>
    <p>Population has $\mu=50$, $\sigma=10$. Random sample of size $n=100$. Find $P(\bar&#123;X&#125; > 52)$. Use $\Phi(2)=0.9772$.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Sampling distribution:</strong> $E[\bar&#123;X&#125;]=50$, $\text&#123;SE&#125;=\sigma/\sqrt&#123;n&#125;=10/\sqrt&#123;100&#125;=1$. So $\bar&#123;X&#125; \approx N(50,\,1^2)$.</p>
    <p><strong>Standardize:</strong> $z=(52-50)/1=2$.</p>
    <p><strong>Probability:</strong> $P(\bar&#123;X&#125;>52)=1-\Phi(2)=1-0.9772=0.0228$.</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">Steps: identify $\mu$, $\sigma$, $n$ → compute SE $= \sigma/\sqrt&#123;n&#125;$ → standardize with SE (not $\sigma$) → look up $\Phi$.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">P(X̄ > 52) ≈ 0.0228</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 2 · GATE 2025 Q40 — CLT to approximate Binomial (MCQ)</span>
    <p>$Y = \sum_&#123;i=1&#125;^&#123;300&#125; X_i$ with $X_i \sim \text&#123;i.i.d. Bernoulli&#125;(0.25)$. Using CLT, $P(60 \le Y \le 90) \approx$ ($\varphi$ = standard normal CDF):<br>
    (A) $\varphi(2)-\varphi(-2)$ &nbsp; (B) $\varphi(1)-\varphi(-1)$ &nbsp; (C) $\varphi(3)-\varphi(-3)$ &nbsp; (D) $\varphi(90)-\varphi(60)$</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Identify:</strong> $Y \sim \text&#123;Binomial&#125;(300, 0.25)$, so mean $= np = 75$, variance $= np(1-p) = 56.25$, SD $= 7.5$.</p>
    <p><strong>CLT:</strong> $Y \approx N(75, 7.5^2)$.</p>
    <p><strong>Standardize endpoints:</strong> $(60-75)/7.5 = -2$; $(90-75)/7.5 = +2$.</p>
    <p><strong>Probability:</strong> $P(60 \le Y \le 90) \approx \varphi(2)-\varphi(-2)$.</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">Trap: (D) looks direct but $\varphi(90)-\varphi(60)$ uses the raw values as z-scores — completely wrong. Always standardize first.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">Answer: (A) φ(2) − φ(−2)</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 3 · GATE 2025 Q36 — Variance of a chi-squared(1) variable (MCQ)</span>
    <p>$Z = (X-\mu)/\sigma$ where $X \sim N(\mu,\sigma^2)$. Let $Y = Z^2$. The variance of $Y$ is:<br>
    (A) 1 &nbsp; (B) 2 &nbsp; (C) 3 &nbsp; (D) 4</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Recognize:</strong> $Z \sim N(0,1)$, so $Y = Z^2 \sim \chi^2(1)$ (squared standard normal with $k=1$).</p>
    <p><strong>Formula:</strong> $\text&#123;Var&#125;(\chi^2(k)) = 2k$, so $\text&#123;Var&#125;(Y) = 2(1) = 2$.</p>
    <p><strong>Direct check:</strong> $E[Z^2]=1$, $E[Z^4]=3$ (4th moment of $N(0,1)$), so $\text&#123;Var&#125;(Z^2) = E[Z^4]-(E[Z^2])^2 = 3-1=2$. ✓</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);">This is the easiest route on the exam: recognize $Z^2 \sim \chi^2(1)$, then $\text&#123;Var&#125; = 2k = 2$. One line.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">Answer: (B) 2</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 4 · GATE 2026 Q53 — Sums of squared normals &amp; sample variance (MSQ · Hard)</span>
    <p>$X_1,\dots,X_n$ i.i.d. $N(0,1)$; $\bar&#123;X&#125;=(1/n)\sum X_i$. Which are correct?<br>
    (A) $\sum X_i^2 \sim \chi^2(n)$ &nbsp; (B) $\sum(X_i-\bar&#123;X&#125;)^2 \sim \chi^2(n-1)$ &nbsp; (C) $X_1^2+X_n^2 \sim \text&#123;Exponential&#125;(\text&#123;mean &#125;2)$ &nbsp; (D) $(\sqrt&#123;n&#125;\cdot\bar&#123;X&#125;)^2 \sim \chi^2(2)$</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>(A) TRUE.</strong> $\sum_&#123;i=1&#125;^n X_i^2$ is a sum of $n$ squared standard normals → $\chi^2(n)$ by definition.</p>
    <p><strong>(B) TRUE.</strong> Sample variance form: one degree of freedom is consumed estimating $\bar&#123;X&#125;$, giving $\chi^2(n-1)$. (The $n$-vs-$(n-1)$ GATE trap.)</p>
    <p><strong>(C) TRUE.</strong> $X_1^2+X_n^2 \sim \chi^2(2)$ (two squared standard normals). And $\chi^2(2) = \text&#123;Exponential&#125;(\text&#123;mean &#125;2)$ — the special identity.</p>
    <p><strong>(D) FALSE.</strong> $\sqrt&#123;n&#125;\cdot\bar&#123;X&#125; \sim N(0,1)$, so its square $\sim \chi^2(1)$, not $\chi^2(2)$. Trap: $n$ in the expression ≠ df.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">Answer: (A), (B), (C)</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ GATE ANGLE ═══ -->
<div class="gd-gate-box">
  <div class="gd-gate-box__title">GATE DA Angle</div>
  <p><strong>SE = σ/√n, Var(X̄) = σ²/n.</strong> The most-tested formulas. Standardize $\bar&#123;X&#125;$ with SE (not $\sigma$): $z = (\bar&#123;X&#125; - \mu)/(\sigma/\sqrt&#123;n&#125;)$. Setting SE = $\sigma$ or Var($\bar&#123;X&#125;$) = $\sigma^2$ is the top mistake.</p>
  <p><strong>CLT works for ANY parent</strong> with finite variance — it does NOT require a normal parent. (2025 Q40 applied it to Bernoulli sums.) Steps: mean and variance from parent formula, standardize, look up $\Phi$.</p>
  <p><strong>χ²(k): mean $= k$, Var $= 2k$.</strong> A squared standard normal is $\chi^2(1)$ with Var $= 2$. (2025 Q36 was just $k=1$.) Don't swap mean and variance.</p>
  <p><strong>Sample variance → χ²(n−1), not χ²(n).</strong> The $-1$ comes from estimating $\bar&#123;X&#125;$. (2026 Q53 B was designed around this trap.)</p>
  <p><strong>χ²(2) = Exponential(mean 2).</strong> Sum of two squared standard normals is exponential. This identity appears directly in 2026 Q53 C — recognise it immediately.</p>
  <p><strong>To halve CI width, quadruple n</strong> (from $n$ to $4n$). Width $= 2z\sigma/\sqrt&#123;n&#125;$, so $n \to 4n$ → width $\to$ width/2.</p>
</div>

